1    Installation
This README file explains how to install, setup, and run the WITSML CERTIFICATION TEST TOOL.
Instructions are provided for both Windows and Linux. 

MoRe information on how to use the WITSML CERTIFICATION TEST TOOL and the WITSML Test Libraries
can be found in the document "WITSML Certification Testing Tool: Installation and User Guide "  


1.1   Install and Set Up Python Components.
To run the WITSML CERTIFICATION TESTING TOOL, you must have a python interpreter and
specific python utilities installed on your machine.

1.1.1 Install For Windows (Windows 7 64 bit)
The 32-bit version of python has been used for both 32-bit and 64-bit Windows machines.

To install the 32-bit version of python, follow these steps:

  1.  If not already installed, install a Python interpreter.
      Use these instructions to install the Python interpreter 2.7.2
      from www.python.org:
      
      a.  From http://www.python.org/download, download and install the Python 2.7.3 interpreter
          using the proper download format for your machine.

          For example, click on "Python 2.7.3 Windows Installer (x86 32 bit MSI Installer) and
          then click Run. Follow the installation instructions.
      
      b.  Add the Python directory to your path.
          i.   From the desktop, left-click the Start button and Select Control Panel, then System.
          ii.  In the System Properties window, click on the Advanced tab.
          iii. In the Advanced section, click the Environment Variables button. 
          iv.  Finally, in the Environment Variables window,in the Systems Variable section, 
               highlight the Path variable and click the Edit button. 
          v.   Add or modify the path lines with the paths you wish the computer to access. 
	       Each different directory is separated with a semicolon (e.g., add "C:\Python27;" to the
               beginning of the path)
          vi.  For the environment variable changes to take place, You may need to restart any 
               open command window. In some cases, you may need to reboot the computer.

  2.  If not already installed, install setuptools.
      a.  Just in case, first remove all setuptools.pth, setuptools*.egg and
          setuptools*.egg-info files.
      b.  From: http://pypi.python.org/pypi/setuptools#downloads, 
          download and run "setuptools-0.6c11.win32-py2.7.exe (md5)"

  3.  If not already installed, install the lxml python library.
      a.  In your python directory, find the subdirectory with the easy_install script 
          (e.g., c:\Python27\Scripts). 
      b.  In a command window, navigate to this subdirectory and run  easy_install lxml
              > c:
              > cd \Python27\Scripts
              > easy_install lxml==2.3
			  
	NOTE: If you have a problem with step a, you might need to configure your IE with a Proxy. 
        (For IE8, select Tools > Internet Options Connections > LAN Settings, Modify Proxy server settings.)

  4.  If not already installed, install the suds python library:
      a.  In your python directory, find the subdirectory with the easy_install script
          (e.g. c:\Python27\Scripts). 
      b.  In a command window, navigate to this subdirectory and run  easy_install suds
              > c:
              > cd \Python27\Scripts
              > easy_install suds==0.4
              
  5.  If not already installed, install the python-dateutil python library. 
      a.  In your python directory, find the subdirectory with the easy_install script
          (e.g. c:\Python27\Scripts). 
      b.  In a command window, navigate to this subdirectory and run easy_install python-dateutil
              > c:
              > cd \Python27\Scripts
              > easy_install python-dateutil==2.1
              
  6.  If not already installed, install the pytz python library.
      a.  In your python directory, find the subdirectory with the easy_install script
          (e.g. c:\Python27\Scripts). 
      b. In a command window, navigigate to this subdirectory and and run  easy_install pytz
              > c:
              > cd \Python27\Scripts
              > easy_install pytz==2012d                             

1.1.2 Install for Linux

To install python interpreter and utilties for Linus, follow these steps.

Note: This was tested in a machine with CentOS release 5.2.

  1.  If not already installed, install the python interpreter version 2.7.2 
      a.  Download the Gzipped source tar ball from http://www.python.org/download/releases/2.7.2/.

      b.  Extract it and add to your PATH. (export PATH=<dir>/Python-2.7/bin:$PATH )
      
  2.  If not already installed, install the lxml python library version 2.3
              > easy_install lxml==2.3

  3.  If not already installed, install the suds python library version 0.4
              > easy_install suds==0.4
              
  4.  If not already installed, install the python-dateutil python library version 2.1
              > easy_install python-dateutil==2.1
  
  5.  If not already installed, install the pytz python library version 2012d
              > easy_install pytz==2012d


1.2   WITSML CERTIFICATION TEST TOOL Installation and Setup

  1.  To install the tool, go to the trunk directory where you downloaded the WITSML CERTIFICAITON TEST TOOL software
      and install it with setup.py as follows:
              > python setup.py install
			  
      
     The following directories are added under C:\Python27\Lib\site-packages
	            wtl, wsvt, wtools

 
  2.  Setup

  To setup the WITSML CERTIFICATION TEST TOOL, follow these steps:

     a.  Create a server file using the template wtl_server.py (found in the trunck/src/wtl directory).
       

     b.  Give it a DIFFERENT name (any name you want) with the .py extension.
         Make sure you place the created file in a directory that IS NOT under the <installation directory>
         Example:
         <LINUX>
            cd /witsml 
            cp <installation directory>/trunk/src/wtl/wtl_server.py my_server.py

         <WINDOWS>
	    c:
	    cd \witsml 
	    copy <installation directory>\trunk\src\wtl\wtl_server.py my_server.py

     c.  Edit the server file server.py to set the correct login information and
         server parameters for the server you want to test. 

         NOTE: Server parameters vary depending on the test suite being used.
         The WITSML certification script suite provides a template server file
         in <installation directory>/trunk_scripts/datamodel named default_server.py

     d.  Create a directory from which to run the WITSML scripts. 
         Example:
           <LINUX>
               /witsml/scripts
           <WINDOWS>
               c:\witsml\scripts
			
     e.  Create a directory to output the results of executing the tests. 
         Example:
           <LINUX>
            /witsml/results
           <WINDOWS>
            c:\witsml\results		

     f.  In the directory where WITSML scripts will be run, create a configuration file
         with the SAME name ‘wtl_cfg.py’ and format as the configuration file provided in 
         the src/wtl directory.
         For example with the sample directories above:
         <LINUX>
             cd /witsml/scripts 
             cp <installation directory>/trunk/src/wtl/wtl_cfg.py .
         <WINDOWS>
             c:
             cd \witsml\scripts 
             copy <installation directory>\trunk\src\wtl\wtl_cfg.py .

     g.  To set the correct server file and paths in step 1. above, edit the created configuration file wtl_cfg.py.
         For example with the sample directories above:
	     <LINUX>
           # WITSML TEST LIBRARY CONFIGURATION
        
           # Server file
           server_file_directory = '/witsml'
           server_file_name = 'my_server'

           # List of directories containing the test scripts and test suites
           script_directories = [
                              '/witsml/scripts'
                             ]

           # Output directory
           result_directory = ‘/witsml/results’

         <WINDOWS>
           # WITSML TEST LIBRARY CONFIGURATION

           # Server file
           server_file_directory = 'c:\\witsml'
           server_file_name = 'my_server'

           # List of directories containing the test scripts and test suites
           script_directories = [
                               'c:\\witsml\\scripts'
                             ]

           # Output directory
           result_directory = 'c:\\witsml\\results'

          NOTES: 1) The server file name does not include the .py extension
	         2) Make sure the result directory exists.

				
   3.    Run the WITSML CERTIFICATION TEST TOOL.

	   a. copy desired test scripts from <installation directory>\trunk_scripts\accepted
           <LINUX>
            /witsml/scripts
           <WINDOWS>
               c:\witsml\scripts	
		
	   b. To run, go to the scripts directory and type "python testScriptName.py" ( i.e., python test1a.py ) 

